{"id":"1603.00517","submitter":"Mathias Schacht","authors":"Vojt\\v{e}ch R\\\"odl, Andrzej Ruci\\'nski, Mathias Schacht","title":"Ramsey properties of random graphs and Folkman numbers","comments":"20 pages, second version addresses changes arising from the referee\n  report","journal-ref":"Discuss. Math. Graph Theory 27(3) (2017) 755-776","doi":"10.7151/dmgt.1971","report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For two graphs, $G$ and $F$, and an integer $r\\ge2$ we write $G\\rightarrow\n(F)_r$ if every $r$-coloring of the edges of $G$ results in a monochromatic\ncopy of $F$. In 1995, the first two authors established a threshold edge\nprobability for the Ramsey property $G(n,p)\\to (F)_r$, where $G(n,p)$ is a\nrandom graph obtained by including each edge of the complete graph on $n$\nvertices, independently, with probability $p$. The original proof was based on\nthe regularity lemma of Szemer\\'edi and this led to tower-type dependencies\nbetween the involved parameters. Here, for $r=2$, we provide a self-contained\nproof of a quantitative version of the Ramsey threshold theorem with only\ndouble exponential dependencies between the constants. As a corollary we obtain\na double exponential upper bound on the 2-color Folkman numbers. By a different\nproof technique, a similar result was obtained independently by Conlon and\nGowers.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 1 Mar 2016 22:53:44 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 15 Jul 2016 09:24:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-07-18"}
