{"id":"1603.00673","submitter":"Rafe Jones","authors":"Rafe Jones and Alon Levy","title":"Eventually stable rational functions","comments":"18 pages","journal-ref":"Int. J. Number Theory 13(2017), no. 9, 2299-2318","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For a field K, rational function phi in K(z) of degree at least two, and\nalpha in P^1(K), we study the polynomials in K[z] whose roots are given by the\nsolutions to phi^n(z) = alpha, where phi^n denotes the nth iterate of phi. When\nthe number of irreducible factors of these polynomials stabilizes as n grows,\nthe pair (phi, alpha) is called eventually stable over K. We conjecture that\n(phi, alpha) is eventually stable over K when K is any global field and alpha\nany point not periodic under phi (an additional non-isotriviality hypothesis is\nnecessary in the function field case). We prove the conjecture when K has a\ndiscrete valuation for which (1) phi has good reduction and (2) phi acts\nbijectively on all finite residue extensions. As a corollary, we prove for\nthese maps a conjecture of Sookdeo on the finiteness of S-integral points in\nbackwards orbits. We also give several characterizations of eventual stability\nin terms of natural finiteness conditions, and survey previous work on the\nphenomenon.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 2 Mar 2016 12:06:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 2 May 2017 12:01:36 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-24"}
